# Trivy Security Scan Suppressions
# Format: AVD-ID or rule-path
#
# This file contains justified exceptions to Trivy security findings.
# Each suppression MUST have a documented justification explaining:
#   1. WHY the finding is suppressed
#   2. WHAT mitigations are in place
#   3. RISK ACCEPTANCE rationale
#
# DO NOT add suppressions without proper security review and approval.

# ============================================================
# Kubernetes RBAC - Secrets Access (CRITICAL)
# ============================================================
# Rule: KSV-0041 - ClusterRole shouldn't have access to manage resource 'secrets'
# Affected Files:
#   - deploy/rbac/role.yaml (line 152)
#   - deploy/rbac/role-admin.yaml (line 81)
#   - deploy/install.yaml (embedded RBAC)
#
# JUSTIFICATION:
#   REQUIRED FOR CORE FUNCTIONALITY - DNS operator MUST manage RNDC secrets for BIND9 authentication.
#   RNDC (Remote Name Daemon Control) keys are used to authenticate DNS zone updates to BIND9 servers.
#   Without secrets access, the operator cannot create/read/delete RNDC keys, breaking core functionality.
#
# MITIGATIONS:
#   1. Namespace-scoped via RoleBinding (not ClusterRoleBinding) - limits blast radius
#   2. Minimal verbs - bindy-role only has get/list/watch/create/patch/delete (no "update")
#   3. Purpose-specific secrets - only creates/reads secrets with "bindy-rndc-" prefix
#   4. Audit logging enabled - all secret operations logged for compliance (PCI-DSS 10.2)
#   5. RBAC separation - admin role is separate, requires explicit binding by cluster administrator
#   6. ServiceAccount token auto-mount disabled - reduces attack surface
#
# RISK ACCEPTANCE:
#   Secrets access is unavoidable for DNS operator authentication requirements.
#   Namespace isolation and audit logging provide defense-in-depth.
#
# COMPLIANCE:
#   - PCI-DSS 7.1.2 (minimal permissions for sensitive data)
#   - NIST SP 800-190 (container secrets management)
#
AVD-KSV-0041

# ============================================================
# Kubernetes RBAC - Services/Endpoints Access (HIGH)
# ============================================================
# Rule: KSV-0056 - ClusterRole should not have write access to network resources
# Affected Files:
#   - deploy/rbac/role.yaml (line 130)
#   - deploy/rbac/role-admin.yaml (line 67)
#   - deploy/install.yaml (embedded RBAC)
#
# JUSTIFICATION:
#   REQUIRED FOR CORE FUNCTIONALITY - DNS operator MUST manage Services to expose BIND9 servers.
#   Kubernetes Services are necessary for routing DNS traffic (UDP/TCP port 53) to BIND9 pods.
#   Without service management, DNS queries cannot reach the DNS servers.
#
# MITIGATIONS:
#   1. Namespace-scoped via RoleBinding - cannot intercept traffic in other namespaces
#   2. Owner references - Services are bound to Bind9Instance resources (automatic cleanup on delete)
#   3. Finalizers - Explicit deletion only when parent Bind9Instance is deleted
#   4. Service selectors - Only route traffic to pods owned by this operator
#   5. NetworkPolicy enforcement - Traffic interception prevented by cluster NetworkPolicies
#   6. Endpoints are READ-ONLY - operator only watches endpoints, never modifies them
#
# RISK ACCEPTANCE:
#   Service management is fundamental to DNS server operation. Network policies and namespace
#   isolation provide defense-in-depth against traffic interception.
#
# COMPLIANCE:
#   - NIST SP 800-190 (container orchestration security)
#   - CIS Kubernetes Benchmark 5.1.5 (minimize access to network services)
#
AVD-KSV-0056

# ============================================================
# Example ConfigMap - False Positive (HIGH)
# ============================================================
# Rule: KSV-0109 - ConfigMap stores secrets
# Affected Files:
#   - examples/bind9-cluster-with-rotation.yaml (line 169)
#
# JUSTIFICATION:
#   FALSE POSITIVE - This ConfigMap contains example kubectl commands for monitoring RNDC rotation.
#   The bash script references Kubernetes Secret resource names (e.g., "kubectl get secret $SECRET")
#   but does NOT store actual secret values. Trivy incorrectly detects the word "Secret" in the
#   variable names and kubectl commands.
#
# CONTENT:
#   Monitoring script that demonstrates how to check RNDC rotation status using kubectl commands.
#   Example: kubectl annotate secret $SECRET bindy.firestoned.io/force-rotation="true"
#
# VERIFICATION:
#   Inspect examples/bind9-cluster-with-rotation.yaml lines 183-241 to verify no secret data is stored.
#
AVD-KSV-0109
